<subSubSection id="70E51A85FF952542FF4BAA1AA82ACB0D" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph id="3840490EFF952542FF4BAA1AAEA2CC2D" blockId="10.[151,1437,261,1116]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF952542FF4BAA1AADA8CEB6" bold="true" box="[199,415,369,396]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description. Male</emphasis>
. Whole fly as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FDC6AA1AAEA9CEB6" box="[586,670,369,396]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[176,1405,205,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[161,1427,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 57, whole fly; 58, right half of frons; 59, proboscis, palps and antennae; 60, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 61, scutellum; 62, left face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573380" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573380/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
. Frons as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FC98AA1AAF5FCEB6" box="[788,872,369,396]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[176,1405,205,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[161,1427,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 57, whole fly; 58, right half of frons; 59, proboscis, palps and antennae; 60, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 61, scutellum; 62, left face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573380" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573380/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
, with very fine microsetae. Cheek with 4 bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and more robust. Antennae, palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FBCBAAFEA8ADCE8A" box="[1095,1178,405,432]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[176,1405,205,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[161,1427,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 57, whole fly; 58, right half of frons; 59, proboscis, palps and antennae; 60, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 61, scutellum; 62, left face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573380" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573380/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 59</figureCitation>
, the postpedicels lacking SPS vesicles. Thorax brown, with 3 notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these, and mesopleuron a few small hairs (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FEAFAAB6AD4ECEC2" box="[291,377,477,504]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[176,1405,205,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[161,1427,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 57, whole fly; 58, right half of frons; 59, proboscis, palps and antennae; 60, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 61, scutellum; 62, left face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573380" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573380/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 60</figureCitation>
). Scutellum with an anterior pair of very small hairs and a posterior pair of bristles (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FAB6AAB6A9B8CEC2" box="[1338,1423,477,504]" captionStart="FIGURES 57–62" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[176,1405,205,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[161,1427,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 57–62. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 57, whole fly; 58, right half of frons; 59, proboscis, palps and antennae; 60, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 61, scutellum; 62, left face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573380" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573380/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tergites brown with small hairs only a little longer at rear of T6. Venter brownish gray, and with small hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FDDCA94EAEF8CD7A" box="[592,719,549,576]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 57–62" captionStart-1="FIGURES 63–69" captionStartId-0="11.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionStartId-1="12.[151,264,1504,1529]" captionTargetBox-0="[176,1405,205,1909]" captionTargetBox-1="[197,1387,181,1475]" captionTargetId-0="figure@11.[161,1427,181,1920]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[195,1391,181,1478]" captionTargetPageId-0="11" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGURES 57–62. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 57, whole fly; 58, right half of frons; 59, proboscis, palps and antennae; 60, mesopleuron and notopleuron; 61, scutellum; 62, left face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." captionText-1="FIGURES 63–69. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 63, left face of hypandrium; 64, right face of hypopygium; 65, right handrium lobe; 66, front tarsus; 67, mid femur and tibia; 68, hind femur; 69, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573380" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573382" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3573380/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3573382/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Figs 62–65</figureCitation>
, with the distinctive right hypandrial lobe as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FB32A94EA939CD7A" box="[1214,1294,549,576]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–69" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1504,1529]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,181,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[195,1391,181,1478]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 63–69. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 63, left face of hypandrium; 64, right face of hypopygium; 65, right handrium lobe; 66, front tarsus; 67, mid femur and tibia; 68, hind femur; 69, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573382/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
, the left lobe being broad and pale. Legs brown but more yellowish brown tarsi. Fore tarsus with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and 5 clearly longer than 4 (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FDF8A906AEFFCDB2" box="[628,712,621,648]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–69" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1504,1529]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,181,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[195,1391,181,1478]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 63–69. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 63, left face of hypandrium; 64, right face of hypopygium; 65, right handrium lobe; 66, front tarsus; 67, mid femur and tibia; 68, hind femur; 69, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573382/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 66</figureCitation>
). Mid femur and tibia as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FC6FA906A802CDBD" box="[995,1077,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–69" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1504,1529]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,181,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[195,1391,181,1478]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 63–69. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 63, left face of hypandrium; 64, right face of hypopygium; 65, right handrium lobe; 66, front tarsus; 67, mid femur and tibia; 68, hind femur; 69, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573382/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
, with the dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extending about 0.6 times its length. Hind femur as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FCCFA9FAAFA3CD91" box="[835,916,657,683]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–69" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1504,1529]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,181,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[195,1391,181,1478]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 63–69. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 63, left face of hypandrium; 64, right face of hypopygium; 65, right handrium lobe; 66, front tarsus; 67, mid femur and tibia; 68, hind femur; 69, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573382/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
. Hind tibia with about a dozen moderately differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF952542FB65A9DEA90DCDEA" box="[1257,1338,693,720]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–69" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1504,1529]" captionTargetBox="[197,1387,181,1475]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[195,1391,181,1478]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 63–69. Megaselia quirogoliensis n. sp. male. 63, left face of hypandrium; 64, right face of hypopygium; 65, right handrium lobe; 66, front tarsus; 67, mid femur and tibia; 68, hind femur; 69, wing. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573382" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573382/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
) 1.5–2.0 mm long. Costal index 0.39. Costal ratios 4.45: 1.18: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity id="FF07E4EBFF952542FBCAA9B2A89DCDCE" box="[1094,1194,729,756]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="0.06">0.06 mm</quantity>
long. No hair at base of vein 3. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3840490EFF952542FF4BA84AA82ACB0D" blockId="10.[151,1437,261,1116]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF952542FF4BA84AAD6ACC06" bold="true" box="[199,349,801,828]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Recognition.</emphasis>
The modified mid femora characterizes a limited number of species, whose Palaearctic members are covered by 
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF952542FEC0A82EADC7CC65" author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[332,496,837,863]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="687 - 695" refId="ref21289" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2004) The distinctive Megaselia deltomera Schmitz 1924 (Diptera: Phoridae) belongs to a complex of sibling species. Annales Zoologici, Warszawa, 54, 687 - 695." type="journal article" year="2004">Disney (2004)</bibRefCitation>
supplemented by 
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF952542FD49A82EAFDCCC65" author="Disney, R. H. L. &amp; Withers, P." box="[709,1003,837,863]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="29 - 41" refId="ref21537" refString="Disney, R. H. L. &amp; Withers, P. (2011) Scuttle flies (Diptera, Phoridae) reared from tree rotholes in France, including three new species of Megaselia Rondani. Fragmenta faunistica, 54, 29 - 41. https: // doi. org / 10.3161 / 00159301 FF 2011.54.1.029" type="journal article" year="2011">Disney &amp; Withers (2011)</bibRefCitation>
. The Nearctic species are covered by 
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF952542FF1BA802AD53CCBE" author="Borgmeier, T." box="[151,356,873,900]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="257 - 416" refId="ref20921" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1964) Revision of the North American Phorid flies. Part II. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Aphiochaeta (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 7, 257 - 416." type="journal article" year="1964">Borgmeier (1964)</bibRefCitation>
. An Anfrotropical species is covered by 
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF952542FCBCA802AFE2CCB9" author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[816,981,873,899]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="189 - 193" refId="ref21195" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1982) Two new species of Afrotropical Megaselia (Diptera: Phoridae). Entomologist's Monthly Magazine, 118, 189 - 193." type="journal article" year="1982">Disney (1982)</bibRefCitation>
. In the key to Palaearctic species it runs to couplet 3 lead 
<specimenCount id="2EF98287FF952542FEDBA8E6ADBDCC9D" box="[343,394,909,935]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="generic">
2 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF952542FEE0A8E5ADBDCC9D" authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" box="[364,394,910,935]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epandquadriata">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF952542FEE0A8E5ADBDCC9D" box="[364,394,910,935]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
epandquadriata Disney and the subsequently described 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF952542FB8FA8E5A917CC9D" authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="2011" box="[1027,1312,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deltofemoralis">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF952542FB8FA8E5A8FDCC9D" box="[1027,1226,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. deltofemoralis</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
runs to the same point but their hypopygia and mid femora are different. Likewise, the Nearctic species covered by Borgmeier; but the mid femur of the subsequently described 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF952542FD33A8BDA899CCCA" authority="Hartop, Brown &amp; Disney (2015)" authorityName="Hartop, Brown &amp; Disney" authorityYear="2015" box="[703,1198,981,1008]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pisanoi">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF952542FD33A8BDAF00CCD5" box="[703,823,982,1007]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. pisanoi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF952542FCB3A8BDA899CCCA" author="Hartop, E. A. &amp; Brown, B. V. &amp; Disney, R. H. L." box="[831,1198,981,1008]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="451 - 484" refId="ref21637" refString="Hartop, E. A., Brown, B. V. &amp; Disney, R. H. L. (2015) Opportunity in our ignorance of urban biodiversity: study reveals 30 new species and one new Nearctic record for Megaselia (Diptera Phoridae) in Los Angeles (California, USA). Zootaxa, 3941 (4), 451 - 484. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3941.4.1" type="journal article" year="2015">Hartop, Brown &amp; Disney (2015)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is similar, but different from, our species. However, its hypopygium is clearly different. The mid femur of the Afrotropical 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF952542FAA9A891ACD1CB0D" authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="1982" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morani">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF952542FAA9A891A9ABCB29" box="[1317,1436,1018,1043]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">M. morani</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
is similar but its hypopygium is clearly different and its haltere is brown.
</paragraph>
